import pandas as pd

def load_dataset(file_name, **kwargs):
    try:
        data = pd.read_csv(file_name, **kwargs)
    except FileNotFoundError:
        raise FileNotFoundError(f"Cannot find {file_name}, please either place the file in the same directory as this notebook, or provide the full path")
    labels = data.values[:, -1]
    data = data.values[:, :-1]
    return data, labels

Q1.1 (6 marks)¶

Q1.1a (2 marks)¶

Using simple.csv, run the K-Means and single-linkage algorithms (available in scikit-learn) on the dataset, using the true number of clusters ($K=5$). Produce a graph (e.g. bar chart) showing the performance (measured using the adjusted rand index) across 10 independent runs. Discuss the results obtained, using your knowledge of how the algorithms work to explain why the behaviour observed occurred.

Hints:

  • This question is more difficult without the use of error bars!
  • For single-linkage, use AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=5, linkage="single")
  • For KMeans, use KMeans(n_clusters=5, init="random", n_init=1) as arguments.

Q1.1a Answer¶

In [ ]:
# import libraries
import numpy as np
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering, KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import adjusted_rand_score, silhouette_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
import seaborn as sns
from datetime import datetime
In [ ]:
# Please enter any relevant code for Q1.1a below.
# You can use multiple cells if it helps break up the code execution
kmeans_ari_list = []
singleLinkage_ari_list = []

for i in range(10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=5, init="random", n_init=1)
    kmeans_fit = kmeans.fit(simple_data)

    singleLinkage = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=5, linkage="single")
    singleLinkage_fit = singleLinkage.fit(simple_data)

    kmeans_ari_list.append(adjusted_rand_score(simple_labels, kmeans_fit.labels_))
    singleLinkage_ari_list.append(adjusted_rand_score(simple_labels, singleLinkage_fit.labels_))

kmeans_ari_mean = np.mean(kmeans_ari_list)
singleLinkage_ari_mean = np.mean(singleLinkage_ari_list)

kmeans_ari_std = np.std(kmeans_ari_list)
singleLinkage_ari_std = np.std(singleLinkage_ari_list)
In [ ]:
x_strings = ["K Means", "Single Linkage"]
y_height = [kmeans_ari_mean, singleLinkage_ari_mean]
error = [kmeans_ari_std, singleLinkage_ari_std]

plt.bar(x=x_strings, height=y_height, yerr=error, align="center", ecolor="black", capsize=10, alpha=0.5)
plt.show()

Q1.1a Analysis¶

As can be seen from the above figure, the average adjusted Rand score of kmeans is about 0.8. Through multiple runs, it can be found that this score will be different, fluctuating between 0.6 and 0.9. The adjusted Rand Score of linkage algorithm is 0.7 every time, and there is no fluctuation. Combined with error bar, i.e. standard deviation, K-Means is in low stability, because this algorithm clustered by initialized points randomly and the clustering result depends on the position of the initial points.

For better explanation, visualize the data and the center points obtained by K-Means clustering (both correct and wrong center points).

In [ ]:
centers = KMeans(n_clusters=5, init="random", n_init=1).fit(simple_data).cluster_centers_

plt.scatter(simple_data[:,0], simple_data[:,1])
plt.scatter(centers[:,0], centers[:,1])
plt.show()
In [ ]:
centers = KMeans(n_clusters=5, init="random", n_init=1).fit(simple_data).cluster_centers_

plt.scatter(simple_data[:,0], simple_data[:,1])
plt.scatter(centers[:,0], centers[:,1])
plt.show()

The data in this dataset exist in spheres or bars, and there are intervals between each cluster.

K-Means is an algorithm based on centroid clustering. As mentioned above, the initial centroids are random, and there will be cases where two clusters share one centroid, or one cluster has two centroids. In this case, the ARI of K-Means is low. In another case, the centroids is correct initially, and then the cluster result is correct, which makes the API high. Therefore, the performance of K-Means is unstable (n_init=1 means it runs only once).

Single-Linkage algorithm is to treat each point as a cluster, and then merge the two nearest clusters. Three clusters in this dataset are spaced closely, so incorrect clustering may occur, and the API is low. However, the distances of each cluster does not change with each run, and the final clustering results are the same, which makes the Single-Linkage algorithm very stable.

Q1.2 (5 marks)¶

Q1.2a (3 marks)¶

Discuss two methods that can be used to estimate the true number of clusters. A discussion of the suitability and potential issues with each method is expected. No marks are given beyond the first two methods.

Q1.2a Answer¶

In [ ]:
# Please enter any relevant code for Q1.2a below
# You can use multiple cells if it helps

First is Elbow Method:

The function is: $D_k = \sum_{i=1}^{all \ clusters}{\sum_{j=1}^{all \ points \ in \ that \ cluster} {dist(c_i,x_j)^2}}$

where $c_i$ is the point of cluster center of $i^{th}$ cluster, ${x_j}$ is the $j^{th}$ point in that cluster ($j^{th}$ is for all points in that cluster)

By comparing the D value of the different clusters numbers, choose the "elbow" point as the best cluster number. ("elbow" point: For discriminative data, the d value will be greatly improved when a certain critical point is reached, and then slowly decrease, this critical point can be considered as a point with better clustering performance)

Suitability: The discriminative data that have "elbow" point

Potential issues: Some data may don't have "elbow" point. If the d values are not vary too much or keep decrease, then this method is not suitable for the data.

Second is Silhouette Method:

The function is: $s_i = \frac {(b_i - a_i)} { max(a_i, b_i)}$

where $a_i$ is the mean value of the distance between $i^{th}$ sample and each other in the cluster, $b_i$ is the mean value from the $i^{th}$ sample to the nearest other cluster samples.

$s_i$ is in range $[-1,1]$, for a clustering task, the samples should be as close as possible within the cluster and as far away from each other as possible. If $s_i$ is close to 1, sample i clustering is reasonable; If $s_i$ is close to - 1, sample i should be classified into another cluster; If $s_i$ is approximately 0, it means that sample i is on the boundary of two clusters.

Suitability: not a large dataset

Potential issues: This method is computationally expensive and time complexity is very high. Because it evaluate every point in dataset. It is not a good choice for large data sets.

Q1.2b (2 marks)¶

Using the simple.csv dataset, apply one of the two methods discussed in Q1.2a to estimate the true number of clusters. Was the estimate correct? Discuss your result.

Q1.2b Answer¶

Elbow Method is used for this question

Assumeing that the cluster number K is unknown, so first a range from 1 to 100 is used to check the "elbow" point. To be more precisely, n_init=10 is used.

In [ ]:
# Please enter any relevant code for Q1.2b below
# You can use multiple cells if it helps
simple_data, simple_labels = load_dataset("simple.csv")

sum_distance_list = []
for i in ([1] + [j for j in range(10,100,10)]):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init="random", n_init=10)
    kmeans_fit = kmeans.fit(simple_data)
    sum_distance_list.append(kmeans_fit.inertia_)

plt.plot(([1] + [j for j in range(10,100,10)]), sum_distance_list)
plt.show()

From above figure, it shows that "elbow" point in 0 to 10. Now check the range from 0 to 10

In [ ]:
sum_distance_list = []
for i in range(1,11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init="random", n_init=10)
    kmeans_fit = kmeans.fit(simple_data)
    sum_distance_list.append(kmeans_fit.inertia_)

plt.plot(range(1,11), sum_distance_list, "o-")
plt.show()

Untill now, it's hard to decide which number is K. 4 and 5 both seems like "elbow" point. By definition, there is a high probability that 4 will be selected as the "elbow" point.

Here is used the second method - Silhouette Method to further determine the K value.

In [ ]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, init="random", n_init=10).fit(simple_data)
silhouette_score_4 = silhouette_score(simple_data, kmeans.labels_)

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=5, init="random", n_init=10).fit(simple_data)
silhouette_score_5 = silhouette_score(simple_data, kmeans.labels_)

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=6, init="random", n_init=10).fit(simple_data)
silhouette_score_6 = silhouette_score(simple_data, kmeans.labels_)

print("K=4 slihouette score: ", silhouette_score_4)
print("K=5 slihouette score: ", silhouette_score_5)
print("K=6 slihouette score: ", silhouette_score_6)

K=4 slihouette score:  0.6906886240290357
K=5 slihouette score:  0.7325759710267562
K=6 slihouette score:  0.6004950508372273

Now K=5 is the best number of clusters as it has the highest slihouette score.

In conclusion, for this question, there is an "elbow" point in the dataset, but the elbow method cannot determine the specific K value, and it is easy to select the wrong "elbow" point as 4. However, in combination with the silhouette method, the K value can be finally determined. The advantage is that it avoids the computational complexity of the silhouette method and can find the specific K value in a small range.

Calculate the Recency Score, Frequency Score and Monetary Score. Then RFM Score is the sum of all scores.

In [ ]:
rfm["Recency Score"] = pd.qcut(rfm["Recency"], q=12, labels=range(12,0,-1)).astype("int")
rfm["Frequency Score"] = (rfm["Frequency"]/10).aggregate(lambda x: int(x))
rfm["Monetary Score"] = pd.qcut(rfm["Monetary"], q=9, labels=range(1,10,1)).astype("int")
rfm["RFM Score"] = rfm["Recency Score"] + rfm["Frequency Score"] + rfm["Monetary Score"]

K=4 is used for clustering, so there are 4 groups. Above is the mean value depend on different groups. From the perspective of enterprises, people who buy recently, spend a large amount of money and have a high frequency are loyal customers. On the contrary, they can be regarded as a tourist. Different strategies can be formulated for different groups of people.

Group 0: The average recent purchase date of this group of customers is more than 400 days, with medium frequency and cost. These customers may have come to shop sometimes before, but they are not shopping now for some reason. This group should be regarded as losing customers.

Group 1: This group of customers did not shop for the longest time, with the lowest frequency and cost. These customers should just happen to browse through the goods and buy them. This group of customers should be regarded as tourists.

Group 2: This group of customers buy recently and frequently, and the price is large. This group should be regarded as loyal customers.

Group 3: This group of customers is not long from the latest purchase date, the purchase frequency is higher than the average level, and the amount is in the upper middle. This group of customers should be regarded as potential loyal customers

Question 2: Itemset Rule Mining (4 marks)¶

For this question, we will be using a real-world dataset which gives the votes of 435 U.S. congressmen on 16 key issues gathered in the mid-1980s, and also includes their party affiliation as a binary attribute. This is a purely nominal dataset with some missing values (corresponding to abstentions). It is normally treated as a classification problem, the task being to predict party affiliation based on voting patterns. However, association-rule mining can also be applied to this data to seek interesting associations.

We will be using Weka, both for its utility for itemset rule mining, and to use a different approach for exploring data. You should have some experience using Weka from the first (non-assessed) week.

You may need to take screenshots of Weka and include them in your answer below, or copy & paste the relevant rules. Please ensure that your answer and rules are clearly legible.

Q2.1 (3 marks)¶

In Weka, run Apriori on this dataset using default settings. Comment on any patterns you see in the rules that are generated. Also discuss their support, confidence, and lift, demonstrating that you understand how they are calculated, their role, and how to interpret these values.

Analysis¶

Term Explaination

Support: The proportion of itemsets that appear in the database. It can be calculated by the number of occurrences of the itemset in the database divided by the number of total itemsets in the database.

Confidence: Confidence(A->B) is probability of occurrence of B on the premise that A has already been given. It can be calculated by the Support(A∪B) divided by Support(A)

Lift: Lift(A->B) is the increase in the ratio of B occur when A occur. If value is 1, then no association between A and B. If value is greater than 1, it implies B likely to occur when A occurs. If value is less than 1, it means B is unlikely to occur when x occurs. It can be calculated by Confidence(A->B) divided by Support(B)

For this dataset, The frequent itemsets L(1) contains 20 instances, the itemsets L(2) contains 17 instances, the frequent itemsets L(3) contain 6 instances, and the frequent itemsets L(4) contains only 1 instance.

From the first rule, it can be seen that Democrat supports adoption-of-the-budget-resolution and opposes the physician-fee-freeze. The lift value is 1.63 means that a person who support adoption-of-the-budget-resolution and opposes the physician-fee-freeze is more likely to be a Democrat. Combined with the confidence value of 1, then it is certain that the person must be a Democrat. There are 219 data support this rule. It is strongly associated with Democrat in support of adoption-of-the-budget-resolution and not support of physician-fee-freeze.

This analysis also applies to rule 2, 3, 4, 5, 9.

It should be noted that the confidence of 5 and 9 are 0.99 and 0.97, and the lift is 1.62 and 1.57, respectively. It shows that most of those who oppose physician-fee-freeze are likely a Democrats, most of those who oppose el-salvador-aid and most of those who support aid-to-nicaraguan-contras are likely a Democrats, not 100%.

From the sisth rule, Democrat who opposes el-salvador-aid is likely to support aid-to-nicaraguan-contras. It is indicated by lift = 1.77 and conf = 0.98 that if a Democrat opposes el-salvador-aid, it is very likely to support aid-to-nicaraguan-contras.

This analysis also applies to rule 7,8,10

Overall, it can be infered that democrat trends to opposes physician-fee-freeze, education-spending and el-salvador-aid, more likely to support adoption-of-the-budget-resolution and aid-to-nicaraguan-contras.

Q2.2 (1 mark)¶

It is interesting to see that none of the rules in the default output involve class = republican. Why do you think that is?

Q2.2 Answer¶

As can be seen from the figure below, the number of votes for republican and democrat differs approximately 100 votes. Then for each attribute, if republican is biased towards support, then democrat must be biased towards opposition (and vice versa, like physician-fee-freeze arrtibute in figure). However, there is more democrat, so the dominance is stronger.

The support value of the apriori algorithm is to analyze each item set. If there are few itemsets, there will be fewer frequent sets generated subsequently. The itemsets of democrate appear frequently, so there are many subsequent sets. So the output involves more class = democrat, resulting in less class = Republican.
